'''Mark Coeckelbergh''' (born 1975) is a Belgian [[Philosophy of technology|philosopher of technology]]. He is Professor of Philosophy of Media and Technology at the Department of Philosophy of the [[University of Vienna]]<ref name="philosophie.univie.ac.at">{{Cite web|title = Institut für Philosophie » Neuigkeiten Einzelansicht|url = https://philosophie.univie.ac.at/aktuelles/neuigkeiten-einzelansicht/article/univ-prof-dr-mark-coeckelbergh-phd-ma-lic/?tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=160063&cHash=4213c13effbb7d3bbb391bc4b457d85a|website = philosophie.univie.ac.at|accessdate = 2015-11-28}}</ref> and President of the [[Society for Philosophy and Technology]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url = http://www.spt.org/|title = The Society for Philosophy and Technology {{!}} spt.org|website = www.spt.org|access-date = 2016-03-03}}</ref> He also has an affiliation as Professor of Technology and Social Responsibility at [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester, UK]].<ref name="dmu.ac.uk">{{cite web|url=http://www.dmu.ac.uk/about-dmu/academic-staff/technology/mark-coeckelbergh/mark-coeckelbergh.aspx|title=Mark Coeckelbergh|website=dmu.ac.uk}}</ref> Before he was Managing Director of the 3TU Centre for Ethics and Technology<ref name="dmu.ac.uk"/> and a member of the Philosophy Department of the [[University of Twente]].<ref>{{cite web|title=University of Twente|url=http://www.utwente.nl/bms/wijsb/organization/coeckelbergh/|website=utwente.nl/en}}</ref> Before moving to Austria, he has lived and worked in Belgium, the UK, and the Netherlands. He is the author of several books, including Growing Moral Relations (2012),<ref name="Growing Moral Relations">{{cite book|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=M|title=Growing Moral Relations|date=July 2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=9781137025951|url=http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/?sf1=id_product&st1=581716}}</ref> Human Being @ Risk (2013),<ref name="Human Being @ Risk">{{cite book|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=Human Being @ Risk|date=2013|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-94-007-6025-7|url=https://www.springer.com/philosophy/epistemology+and+philosophy+of+science/book/978-94-007-6024-0}}</ref> Environmental Skill (2015),<ref name="Environmental Skill">{{cite book|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=Environmental Skill|date=April 2015|publisher=New York: Routledge|isbn=978-1-13-888557-8}}</ref> Money Machines (2015),<ref name="Money Machines">{{cite book|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=Money Machines|date=May 2015|publisher=Ashgate|isbn=978-1-4724-4508-7|url=http://www.ashgate.com/isbn/9781472445087}}</ref> and New Romantic Cyborgs (2017).<ref>{{Cite book|title=New Romantic Cyborgs|last=Coeckelbergh|first=Mark|publisher=MIT Press|year=2017|isbn=9780262035460|location=|pages=}}</ref> He has also written many articles.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=Journal articles|url=https://coeckelbergh.wordpress.com/journal-articles/|website=wordpress.com}}</ref> He is best known for his work in philosophy of technology and [[Roboethics|ethics of robotics]] and artificial intelligence (AI), he has also published in the areas of [[moral philosophy]] and [[environmental philosophy]].

==Early life and education==
Mark Coeckelbergh was born in 1975 in [[Leuven, Belgium]]. He was first educated in [[social science]]s and [[political science]]s at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven|University of Leuven]] (Licentiaat, 1997),<ref name="education">{{cite web|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=Education|url=https://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=247346929&authType=name&authToken=hDw_&trk=prof-proj-cc-name|website=linkedin.com|publisher=Mark Coeckelbergh}}</ref> before moving to the UK where he studied philosophy. He received his [[master's degree]] from the [[University of East Anglia]] (MA in Social Philosophy, 1999) <ref name="education"/> and his PhD from the [[University of Birmingham]] (PhD in Philosophy, 2003).<ref name="education"/> During the time of his PhD study he also painted, wrote poems, played piano, and worked on [[engineering ethics]] at the [[University of Bath]] (UK) and at the Belgian nuclear research centre [[SCK-CEN]].

==Career==
In 2003 he started teaching at the [[University of Maastricht]] in the Netherlands and in 2007 he was Assistant Professor at the Philosophy Department of the [[University of Twente]], also in the Netherlands.<ref name="linkedin.com">{{cite web|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|url=https://www.linkedin.com/profile/view?id=247346929&authType=name&authToken=hDw_|website=linkedin.com|publisher=mark coeckelbergh|title=Experience}}</ref> In the same year he received the Prize of the Dutch Society for Bioethics (with J. Mesman).<ref>{{cite web|title=Prize of the Dutch Society for Bioethics|url=http://www.maastrichtuniversity.nl/web/Main1/SiteWide/SiteWide11/PrijsBioEthiekVoorMaastrichtseOnderzoeker.htm|website=maastrichtuniversity.nl|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519060733/http://www.maastrichtuniversity.nl/web/Main1/SiteWide/SiteWide11/PrijsBioEthiekVoorMaastrichtseOnderzoeker.htm|archivedate=2015-05-19|df=}}</ref> In Twente he started working on the [[Roboethics|ethics of robotics]]. In 2013 he became Managing Director of the 3TU Centre for Ethics and Technology.<ref name="linkedin.com"/> During his time in Twente he published many articles on philosophy of technology (especially robotics) and he was regularly interviewed about the ethics of drone technology. In 2014 he was appointed full professor, before the age of 40, at the Centre of Computing and Social Responsibility, [[De Montfort University]] in [[Leicester, UK]].<ref name="linkedin.com"/> In 2014 he was nominated for the [[World Technology Awards]] in the Ethics category.<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 World Technology Award Nominees|url=http://www.wtn.net/summit-2014/world-technology-award-nominees|website=wtn.net}}</ref> In December 2015 he joined the Department of Philosophy of the [[University of Vienna]] as full Professor of Philosophy of Media and Technology.<ref name="philosophie.univie.ac.at"/>
Coeckelbergh is the President of the [[Society for Philosophy and Technology]],<ref name=":0" /> a member of the High Level Expert Group on Artificial Intelligence for the European Commission, and a member of the newly established Austrian robotics council (Rat für Robotik), inaugurated by the Austrian Ministry for Transport, Innovation and Technology. He is also a member of the editorial advisory boards of Techne,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spt.org/techne-2/|title=Techné: Research in Philosophy and Technology|publisher=}}</ref> Journal of Information, Communication and Ethics in Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emeraldinsight.com/toc/jices/14/2|title=Journal of Information, Communication and Ethics in Society|publisher=}}</ref>  Journal of Posthuman Studies<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.psupress.org/Journals/jnls_JPHS.html|title=Journal of Posthuman Studies|publisher=}}</ref> and Kairos. Journal of Philosophy & Science.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/j/kjps|title=Kairos. Journal of Philosophy & Science|date=2016-03-01|access-date=2017-12-22|language=en}}</ref> Moreover, he is a fellow of the World Technology Network (WTN) and finalist of the World Technology Award 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wtn.net/summit-2017/world-technology-awards-winners-and-finalists|title=2017 World Technology Awards Winners and Finalists {{!}} The World Technology Network|last=|first=|date=|website=bit.ly|access-date=2018-01-29}}</ref> Recently, Coeckelbergh joined the Technical Expertise Committee at the Foundation of Responsible Robotics, along with Charles Ess and Kevin Kelly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://responsiblerobotics.org/technical-expertise-committee/|title=TEC at FRR|publisher=}}</ref>

===Works===

Following his articles on robot ethics and his book Growing Moral Relations,<ref name="palgrave.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.palgrave.com/page/detail/?sf1=id_product&st1=581716|title=Palgrave|work=www.palgrave.com}}</ref> Coeckelbergh has been attributed a 'relational turn' in thinking about moral status.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281645540_The_Issue_of_Moral_Consideration_in_Robot_Ethics|title = The Issue of Moral Consideration in Robot Ethics|date = 19 September 2015|accessdate = 19 September 2015|website = ResearchGate|publisher = ResearchGate|last = Gerdes|first = Anne}}</ref> In his articles Coeckelbergh argues for a [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenological]] and [[Relational theory|relational]] approach to the [[Philosophy of artificial intelligence|philosophy of robotics]]. His theory on 'Social Relationalism' in regards to Artificial Intelligence and Morality is discussed by Gunkel and Cripe in their paper entitled 'Apocalypse Not, or How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Machine'.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gunkel|first1=David J.|last2=Cripe|first2=Billy|title=Apocalypse Not, or How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Machine|journal=Kritikos|date=September 2014|volume=11|page=4.2 Social Relationalism}}</ref> He has published mainly on robot ethics and ICT in health care, but also on many other topics. He also wrote a book on vulnerability and technology (Human Being @ Risk) in which he proposes an 'anthropology of vulnerability' and engages with discussions about human enhancement and [[transhumanism]]. His first books are about freedom, autonomy, and the role of imagination in [[moral reasoning]]. Later books discuss the problem of disengagement and distancing in the use of [[information and communication technologies]] (ICTs) and society's relation to the environment: in Environmental Skill he argues against modern and romantic ways of relating to the environment and in Money Machines he discusses new financial ICTs. In New Romantic Cyborgs he investigates the relation between technology and [[romanticism]] and reflects on what he calls "the end of the machine". He also wrote opinion articles in [[The Guardian]] and in [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sure, Artificial Intelligence May End Our World, But That Is Not the Main Problem|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/12/armageddon-is-not-the-ai-problem/|website=wired.com}}</ref>

