===Reviews===
Work by Coeckelbergh has been responded to by many academics, such as Wendell Wallach of Yale University, USA who regarding the book '[http://www.ashgate.com/isbn/9781472445087 Money Machines]' comments: “Mark Coeckelbergh is recognized internationally for illuminating the manner in which information and communication technologies (ICTs) create new forms of “distancing” and in particular “moral distancing”. This important book extends that analysis to underscore the hidden ways ICTs shape money and global finance, alter relationships, and undermine responsibility”. Also, [http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1467-9655.12683/full Keir James Cecil Martin writes about Money Machines]: "Coeckelbergh’s view of money as a technology of relationality that shortens some geographical and temporal distances, whilst simultaneously widening moral and social gaps (…) has much to offer to anthropological debates on the nature of finance and money."

Marks publications that have been peer-reviewed and received reviews include: Money Machines <ref name="Money Machines"/> 'Environmental Skill',<ref name="Environmental Skill"/> 'Human Being @Risk' <ref name="Human Being @ Risk"/> and 'Growing Moral Relations' <ref name="Growing Moral Relations"/> as well as articles and other peer-reviewed research publications. For example, David Gunkel has written in his review in Ethics and Information Technology that Growing Moral Relations<ref name="palgrave.com"/> is 'a real game changer' and 'a penetrating analysis of moral status'.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Mark Coeckelbergh: Growing moral relations: critique of moral status ascription|url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10676-012-9308-8|journal = Ethics and Information Technology|date = 2013-02-28|issn = 1388-1957|pages = 239–241|volume = 15|issue = 3|doi = 10.1007/s10676-012-9308-8|first = David J.|last = Gunkel}}</ref> Jac Swart has called the book 'an important contribution to animal ethics'<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Mark Coeckelbergh: Growing Moral Relations. Critique of Moral Status Ascription|url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10806-012-9435-6|journal = Journal of Agricultural and Environmental Ethics|date = 2013-03-05|issn = 1187-7863|pages = 1241–1245|volume = 26|issue = 6|doi = 10.1007/s10806-012-9435-6|first = Jac A. A.|last = Swart}}</ref> and Frank Jankunis says in his review that it is 'an impressive contribution to the literature on moral status'.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Frank Jankunis, Mark Coeckelbergh. Growing Moral Relations: Critique of Moral Status Ascription, Environmental Philosophy (Philosophy Documentation Center)|url = https://www.pdcnet.org/pdc/bvdb.nsf/purchase?openform&fp=envirophil&id=envirophil_2013_0010_0002_0116_0119|website = www.pdcnet.org|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref>

Yoni Van Den Eede has called Human Being @ Risk<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.springer.com/us/book/9789400760240|title=Human Being @ Risk|author=Mark Coeckelbergh|publisher=}}</ref> 'one of the most comprehensive and fine-grained in the current literature'<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Where Is the Human? Beyond the Enhancement Debate|url = http://sth.sagepub.com/content/40/1/149|journal = Science, Technology & Human Values|date = 2015-01-01|issn = 0162-2439|pages = 149–162|volume = 40|issue = 1|doi = 10.1177/0162243914551284|first = Yoni Van Den|last = Eede}}</ref> and Pieter Lemmens has written that the book <nowiki>''is thoroughly unique and original in showing the importance and extreme usefulness of philosophical anthropology and the phenomenological tradition for thinking through the consequences of the epochal technological mutations of our time'</nowiki>.<ref name="springer.com">{{Cite book|title = Human Being @ Risk - Enhancement, Technology, and the {{!}} Mark Coeckelbergh {{!}} Springer|url = https://www.springer.com/us/book/9789400760240#reviews}}</ref> Bert-Jaap Koops calls Human Being @ Risk  'an important and original book'<ref name="springer.com"/> and on the website of the Institute for Ethics and Emerging Technologies Nikki Olson writes: 'Coeckelbergh develops an impressive case that all our technological and social measures create new sources of vulnerability … Coeckelbergh drives home an important point for our debates about the human future. … ''Human Being @ Risk'' identifies important choices that we must debate as we imagine and (to a limited extent) plan the future of humanity. It raises issues that are fundamental to ongoing thinking about how to better the human condition.'<ref>{{Cite web|title = Review of Mark Coeckelbergh’s Human Being @ Risk|url = http://ieet.org/index.php/IEET/more/olson20130725|website = ieet.org|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref>

Carl Mitcham writes about Environmental Skill<ref>http://www.taylorandfrancis.com/books/details/9781138885578/{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> that it is 'an insightful argument for an environmental philosophy that draws on the resources of and at the same time extends work in philosophy of technology. The notion of skilled engagement with the world as this has emerged from pragmatism and phenomenology is here deepened and re-thought in an effort to understand and respond to the challenges of living in a techno-transformed nature.'<ref>{{Cite web|title = Environmental Skill: Motivation, Knowledge, and the Possibility of a Non-Romantic Environmental Ethics (Hardback) - Routledge|url = https://www.routledge.com/products/9781138885578|website = www.routledge.com|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref> Jochem Zwier and Andrea Gammon say in their critical but sympathetic review: 'One of the strong points of Coeckelbergh’s diagnosis is that it deepens the discussions regarding environmental concerns and the problem of motivation by laying bare the modern roots of these phenomena.'<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Mark Coeckelbergh: Environmental Skill: Motivation, Knowledge, and the Possibility of a Non-romantic Environmental Ethics|url = https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10746-015-9355-3|journal = Human Studies|date = 2015-07-30|issn = 0163-8548|pages = 1–6|doi = 10.1007/s10746-015-9355-3|first = Jochem|last = Zwier|first2 = Andrea R.|last2 = Gammon}}</ref> Tara Kennedy has published a review of the book in Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews.<ref name="ndpr.nd.edu">{{Cite web|title = Environmental Skill: Motivation, Knowledge, and the Possibility of a Non-Romantic Environmental Ethics // Reviews // Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews // University of Notre Dame|url = http://ndpr.nd.edu/news/61640-environmental-skill-motivation-knowledge-and-the-possibility-of-a-non-romantic-environmental-ethics/|website = ndpr.nd.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-14}}</ref> She writes: 'There is much for contemporary environmentalists to find compelling about Coeckelbergh's account, being not only an interesting analysis of the factors at work in motivation but also a convincing and optimistic approach to the problem.' She questions Coeckelbergh's interpretation of Heidegger but also praises 'Coeckelbergh's effectiveness in articulating a compelling account of the problem of motivation and how the development of an ethics of skilled engagement with the environment, a focus on habit and virtue, would find us better equipped to deal with the environmental crises we face. It is a welcome and interesting addition to a field in need of voices focused on bringing about meaningful, practical change.'<ref name="ndpr.nd.edu"/> And Louke van Wensveen writes in her review in the journal Environmental Ethics that the book reminds us of 'an overly autistic, obsessively controlling tendency in Western philosophical and everyday cultures. Such a distancing pattern and its ideological scaffolding prevent environmental action.'<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.pdcnet.org/pdc/bvdb.nsf/purchase?openform&fp=enviroethics&id=enviroethics_2015_0037_0003_0379_0380|title = Mark Coeckelbergh: Environmental Skill: Motivation, Knowledge, and the Possibility of a Non-Romantic Environmental Ethics  - Louke van Wensveen - Environmental Ethics (Philosophy Documentation Center)|website = www.pdcnet.org|access-date = 2016-03-03}}</ref>

Coeckelbergh's recent book New Romantic Cyborgs has been described as offering 'a whole new way of looking at our use of technologies' and he has been called 'one of the most versatile, profound, and original thinkers in the contemporary philosophy of technology.'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/new-romantic-cyborgs|title=New Romantic Cyborgs (MIT Press)|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> David Seng, University of Arizona, writes: 'One of the strengths of this book is that it is provides a critical process of inquiry and helpful analysis of inherited philosophical orientations regarding the relationship between technology and society.'<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Seng|first=Dave|date=2018-02-14|title=Mark Coeckelbergh , New Romantic Cyborgs: Romanticism, Information Technology, and the End of the Machine . Reviewed by|url=https://journals.uvic.ca/index.php/pir/article/view/17718|journal=Philosophy in Review|language=en|volume=38|issue=1|pages=11–13|issn=1920-8936}}</ref> A review by Roland Legrand for De Tijd especially compliments Mark Coeckelbergh's analysis of virtual worlds, among other aspects of the book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tijd.be/tech-media/technologie/romantische-headset/10011523.html|title=Romantische headset|date=2018-05-14|work=De Tijd|access-date=2018-05-22|language=nl}}</ref>

===In the Media===

Coeckelbergh has appeared regularly in Dutch (and British) media talking about the ethics of drone technology. He has talked about the ethical development of drones in relation to surveillance in an article for Kennislink entitled 'The Irrepressible Drone'<ref>{{cite web|last1=van der Heijden|first1=Roel|last2=Visscher|first2=Robert|title=The irrepressible drone|url=http://www.kennislink.nl/publicaties/de-onbedwingbare-drone|website=kennislink.nl|publisher=Kennislink}}</ref> and about the ethics of drone fighting for Universonline.<ref>{{cite web|last1=van den Eerenbeemt|first1=Adrian|title=The ethics of drone fighting|url=https://universonline.nl/2013/05/16/life-is-buzzing-abroad|website=universonline.nl|ref=page 18}}</ref> He has been interviewed on live radio for BBC radio Leicester <ref name="BBC radio leicester interview">{{cite web|last1=Coeckelbergh|first1=Mark|title=in the media|url=https://coeckelbergh.wordpress.com/in-the-media/|website=wordpress.com|ref=BBC radio leicester interview}}</ref> where on 15 April 2015 he talked about drone technology and discussed robots that cook food.  On 11 June 2013 he appeared on Dutch national television for the Een Vandaag programme also talking about drones <ref>{{cite web|last1=Vandaag|first1=Een|title=Drones - Killer robots|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nVJVKEJEr_U|website=eenvandaag.nl/}}</ref>  and has appeared in articles for the Dutch newspaper Trouw on the subject of environmental philosophy <ref>{{cite news|last1=Kleinjan|first1=Gerrit-Jan|title=Filosoferen in nieuwe oernatuur|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/5009/Archief/article/detail/2446270/2011/06/17/Filosoferen-in-nieuwe-oernatuur.dhtml|agency=Trouw|date=June 17, 2011}}</ref> and 'Down To Earth' magazine (Netherlands) discussing drones for environmental purposes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Technologie en activisme: de dubbelrol van de drone|url=https://downtoearthmagazine.nl/technologie-en-activisme-de-dubbelrol-van-de-drone/|website=downtoearthmagazine.nl|publisher=Down to earth magazine}}</ref> In 2015 he was also interviewed about drones in Stedelijk Interieur, a Dutch magazine on public space.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Preview Stedelijk Interieur 3 2015|url = http://elbamedia.onlinetouch.nl/158#/4|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref>

In August and September 2015 Coeckelbergh's book "Money Machines"<ref>http://www.ashgate.com/isbn/9781472445100</ref> received media attention: he was interviewed on BBC Radio Leicester,<ref>{{Cite web|title = 28/08/2015, Jonathan Lampon - BBC Radio Leicester|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02z0lqb|website = BBC|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref> in the Leicester Mercury<ref>{{Cite web|title = De Montfort University professor warns global financial crash could happen again|url = http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Crashes-warning/story-27724426-detail/story.html|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref> where he warns for a growing reliance on computer algorithms in global finance, and in the Belgian national newspaper De Standaard, which printed a large article on the book in its weekend edition of 12 September 2015. In the De Standaard interview (in Dutch), Coeckelbergh warns that we might delegate too much to technology, and that we lack control and overview. The ethical and societal influence of new technologies may be invisible but is and remains powerful. But, he argues, if technology is part of the problem, it is also part of the solution: we need to develop new, alternative technologies and technological practices, also in the financial world.<ref>{{Cite web|title = ‘De schuldige voor de financiële crisis? De ongrijpbare technologie’  - De Standaard Mobile|url = http://m.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20150911_01862687?shareId=977ffc03a3e645792465be946c8f803ba6e55d75d784299d48800820a7f5e1da699b1261ee3dddc5a4c1ccdb38e3bb74c6d3940df68fc2aa9a3c88ed70747f4c8b1a9b6136ea6fd62c8df76a92993a91|website = m.standaard.be|accessdate = 2015-09-19}}</ref>

Coeckelbergh has also been quoted in international mainstream media such as CNN<ref>{{cite news|last1=Phoebe|first1=Parke|title=Is it cruel to kick a robot dog?|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/02/13/tech/spot-robot-dog-google/index.html|agency=CNN|publisher=CNN|date=February 13, 2015}}</ref> and has a profile at the Guardian <ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Coeckelbergh|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/mark-coeckelbergh|website=theguardian.com|publisher=the guardian}}</ref> due to many comments from readers responding to his article regarding his thoughts about the 2010 Deepwater Horizon oil spill.<ref>{{cite news|title=We're all to blame for the oil spill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2010/jun/09/deepwater-horizon-oil-spill-responsibility-bp|agency=the guardian|publisher=the guardian|date=June 9, 2010}}</ref> On 6 November 2012 Coeckelbergh was Interviewed by Stephen Edwards for a report appearing in the Economist newspaper Intelligence Unit (EIU) exploring the interaction between humans and technology.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Stephen|title=Humans and Machines - the role of people in technology driven organisations (sub heading) Smart systems, Smarter doctors|url=http://www.economistinsights.com/sites/default/files/downloads/EIU_Humans%20&%20machines_FINAL_WEB.pdf|agency=The Economist|date=Nov 6, 2012}}</ref>

In 2014 Coeckelbergh received much response on social media by other philosophers such as Evan Selinger <ref>{{cite web|last1=Selinger|first1=Evan|title=Evan Selinger|url=https://twitter.com/EvanSelinger/status/540510492088098816?t=1&cn=bWVudGlvbg%3D%3D&sig=19cc606194ff171993bd137bb1b28d73773f84c6&al=1&iid=e0bc7c2d4b1a4c0e9692367509cbab4a&autoactions=1417702718&uid=2904865133&nid=4+1264|website=Twitter|publisher=Evan Selinger}}</ref> for his Wired magazine article with posts appearing on Twitter and Facebook.

Coeckelbergh's paper entitled 'Humans, Animals, and Robots: A Phenomenological Approach to Human-Robot Relations' was referenced in an online article for Dailydot.com entitled 'sex and love in the robot age' where human-robot relations were discussed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McHugh|first1=Molly|title=Sex and love in the robot age|url=http://kernelmag.dailydot.com/issue-sections/features-issue-sections/11649/sex-robot-future-roxxxxy/|website=dailydot.com}}</ref> He also wrote an opinion article with Katleen Gabriels in the Dutch newspaper nrc.next which questions a call for banning sex robots and asks attention for (more) pressing societal issues,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Niets mis met  een robotin bed|url = http://www.nrc.nl/next/van/2015/september/26/niets-mis-met-een-robot-in-bed-1537416|accessdate = 2015-09-26}}</ref> and was interviewed about his critical comments on the campaign in the Leicester Mercury.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Banning sex robots 'would be going too far', says De Montfort University professor|url = http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Sex-robots-banned-says-fellow-university/story-27903046-detail/story.html|accessdate = 2015-10-02}}</ref>

In May 2017 he has been included in the top of tech pioneers named by the Belgian newspaper [[De Tijd]], in the category leaders and thinkers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://multimedia.tijd.be/techpioniers/|title=De Tijd - Tech Pioniers|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>

===Public Talks===

Coeckelbergh has given several public talks, including talks concerned with public policy that include an ethics meeting held on 18 May 2011 for UNESCO where he was a panelist and gave a presentation entitled "Freedom, Security, Privacy Or How to Live with new Information and communication Technologies",<ref>{{cite web|title=Cyber and Information Ethics|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/flagship-project-activities/unesco-and-wsis/implementation-and-follow-up/wsis-forum/wsis-forum-2011/cyber-and-information-ethics-action-line-c10-ethics|website=unesco.org}}</ref> and on 15 December 2011 as a panelist for a public talk on the subject of eHealth and Equity in the global health communities for ePractive TV.<ref>{{cite web|title=eHealth and Equity in the Global Health Communities|url=https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/node/125845|website=joinup.ec.europa.eu}}</ref>

===Academics References===
From his more than 100 academic publications Coeckelbergh has been cited hundreds of times, for example his publications in Ethical Theory & Moral Practice, Science, Technology and Human Values, Ethics and Information Technology, International Journal of Social Robotics, and AI & Society. Growing Moral Relations is his most cited book.

