{{about||the present educational institution|Koryo Songgyungwan University|other uses|Seonggyungwan (disambiguation)}} {{main|Gukjagam|Sungkyunkwan}} {{Infobox Korean name | hangul = {{linktext|성|균|관}} | hanja = {{linktext|成|均|館}} | rr = Seonggyun-gwan | mr = Sŏnggyun'gwan | context = north | image = Kaesong-Museum-Building-2014.jpg | caption = }}
The '''Songgyungwan''' was the highest educational institution established during the [[Goryeo|Koryo]] and [[Joseon|Choson Dynasties]]. It opened in 992. The institution consists of the Taesong Temple, Myongnyun Hall and 20 other buildings, including one of the largest wooden buildings to still exist in the [[DPRK]].<ref name=kaesong>{{cite AV media |people= KCNA|year= 2003–2014|title=World Cultural Heritage-Historical Relics in Kaesong |trans-title=|medium= |url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/video/?215+550+440 |accessdate= July 12, 2014|archiveurl= |archivedate= |format= |time=05:54 |location= |publisher=Korea Computer Center in DPRKorea & Foreign Languages Publishing House |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>
Songgyungwan is located two kilometers to the northeast of the center of the city of [[Kaesong]]. Since 1987, it houses the [[Koryo Museum]].<ref name=raskb>{{cite journal |last=CHABANOL |first=ELISABETH |last2= |first2= |date=2005 |title=Study of the Archaeological and Historical Sites of Kaesong |url= http://www.raskb.com/transactions/VOL80/VOL80-4.docx|journal= Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society Korea Branch|publisher=Royal Asiatic Society Korea Branch |volume=80 |issue= |pages=35–57 |doi= |accessdate=5 August 2014}}</ref>
==History== Songgyungwan was originally known as a palace outbuilding called “Taemyon”. The institution was built by [[Munjong of Goryeo|King Munjong, the eleventh king of Koryo]] and was designated as the principal teaching institute in 1089. The facility was given the name '''Songgyungwan''' in 1308. It was later destroyed by fire (in 1592) during the [[Japanese invasions of Korea (1592–98)|Imchin War]]. The institution's twenty buildings date from its reconstruction (which started in 1602); they comply with the characteristics required of a Confucian educational establishment of the period.<ref name=raskb/> [[File:Iphakdo, 5th scene of the Painting Album.jpg|framed|left|Scene from a five panel painting showing the Korean crown prince starting his studies at the Songgyungwan academy.]] It taught [[Confuscianism]] and developed students' ability to handle political and other "practical affairs".<ref name=kaesong/> Songgyungwan prepared young aristocratic men for the civil service and was the center of Confucian studies in the Dynasty.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stowell |first=Jessica A. |last2= |first2= |date=2003 |title=The influence of Confucian values on interpersonal communication in South Korea, compared to China and Japan. |url=http://www.uri.edu/iaics/content/2003v12n4/06%20Jessica%20A.%20Stowell.pdf |journal=Intercultural Communication Studies |publisher=International Association for Intercultural Communication Studies |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=105–116 |doi= |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref> The institution had the particular responsibility of educating the Crown Prince; upon being invested with that title, underwent the state ceremony of ''iphak'' (입학) or commencement of learning at the Songgyungwan in accordance with the code of the ''Iphakrye'' (입학례) as stipulated in the ''Kukcho oryeui'' (국조오례의 "Book on the Five Rites of the State").<ref>{{cite journal |last=Jeong-hye |first=Park |last2= |first2= |date= 2008|title=COURT PAINTINGS ON THE CROWN PRINCES OF THE JOSEON DYNASTY |url=http://211.252.141.1/files/upload/ebook/6/KAaA_02.pdf#page=128 |journal=The International Journal of Korean Art and Archaeology |publisher=National Museum of Korea |volume=2 |issue= |pages=126–165 |doi= |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> The school remained the national seat of learning until the capital was moved to [[Seoul|Hansǒng]] under the [[Joseon Dynasty|Choson Dynasty]], where the current [[Sungkyunkwan University]] became the new national university.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Chongguk |first=Kim |last2=Chinman |first2=Kim |date= October 1961|title= Some Notes on the Sŏnggyun'gwan |url=http://www.raskb.com/transactions/VOL38/Vol038-2.docx |journal= Transactions of the Royal Asiatic Society of Korea|publisher= RASKB|volume= 38|issue=2 |pages=69–91 |doi= |accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref>
[[Jeong Mong-ju|Chong Mong-ju]] passed his civil service examinations at the age of twenty-three and became an instructor of [[Neo-Confucianism]] at the Songgyungwan Academy in 1367.<ref>{{cite journal |last= Choi |first=Changko |last2= |first2= |date=2003 |title=Traditional Legal Thoughts in Korea |url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/jkorl3&div=9&id=&page= |journal=J. Korean L. |publisher=Hein |volume=3 |issue=75 |pages=|doi= |accessdate=12 July 2014}}</ref>
==Current Status== The old buildings are not well-suited to the role of a museum, as they lack proper conditions for the conservation and presentation of works of art, and are ill-suited for the reception of visitors.<ref name=raskb/>
